"CORE_NARRATIVE: Light field depth estimation fundamentally struggles in real-world scenarios because non-Lambertian surfaces disrupt EPI linearity, and traditional frequency-domain methods suffer from feature aliasing at low angular resolutions. By physically decoupling angular signals into illumination, disparity, and material residuals, we extract robust geometric features to accurately isolate and mask material interference. This physics-driven decoupling, paired with a dual-mask routing architecture, effectively restores depth estimation accuracy and generalizability across complex, mixed-reflection scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by contrasting the theoretical promise of light field imaging with its practical collapse on non-Lambertian surfaces, immediately highlighting how low angular resolutions (e.g., 9×9) cause traditional EPI-based depth estimation to fail due to violated linearity assumptions and severe frequency aliasing.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Conclude the related work by demonstrating that 2D-DFT frequency analyses inevitably fail under discrete low angular sampling due to feature aliasing, thereby justifying the critical pivot from frequency-domain filtering to physics-based angular signal decoupling and geometric feature extraction.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: The three-layer physical decomposition model is explicitly designed to bypass frequency aliasing by isolating material residuals, while the GeometricDualMask architecture directly fulfills the motivation by using these decoupled geometric masks to adaptively route Lambertian and non-Lambertian signals into specialized network branches.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the physical decoupling motivation by highlighting the Random Forest's high classification accuracy (89.6%) and the strong effect size of angular gradients (Cohen's d = 0.983), then prove the architectural motivation by demonstrating the dual-mask network's superior depth accuracy and robustness on mixed-reflection datasets.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that shifting from fragile frequency analysis to physical signal decoupling and geometric feature extraction successfully resolves the inherent limitations of low-resolution light fields, establishing an interpretable and unified paradigm for depth estimation in real-world complex scenarios."